DATA CLOUD
BYOL Data Federation

The Data Cloud Bring Your Own Lake (BYOL) data federation is a capability that gives you direct access to partner data. Data federation provides secure and near real-time access to data using zero-copy integration. The data is directly queried without copying it into Data Cloud.

When you deploy a data stream, an external data lake object (DLO) is created. The external DLO is a storage container with metadata for the federated data. The DLO acts as a reference and points to the data physically stored in the partner’s data warehouse or data lake. You can also opt for acceleration to improve performance. For more information, see Acceleration in Data Federation.

You can use the partner data with many Data Cloud features. After you process a job, the resulting data persists in Data Cloud. For example, when you query data from a partner and build a calculated insight based on that data, the resulting calculated insight objects are stored in Data Cloud features. Before using the data in Data Cloud features, you must map the fields listed in the external DLO to the semantic data model. For more information, review data mapping best practices.

NOTE During the testing phase, we observed that the optimal data volume returned from the data lake when acceleration is enabled is up to 20 GB for Snowflake and up to 10 GB for Google BigQuery. For our test datasets, these aforementioned data volumes of 20 GB and 10 GB translate to 500 million and 100 million rows respectively. These numbers are mere representative examples and the number of rows associated can vary for your use-cases.
